1 Introduction

In this tutorial, we show a detailed guide on how to fit reaction norm models accounting for both genomics and enviromics information. This method was first proposed by Jarquin et al. (2014), and was latter expanded and used by several research groups (Campos et al., 2020; Costa-Neto et al., 2021; Toda et al., 2024). This was one of the first initiatives for integrating genomics and enviromics in plant breeding. It is worth mentioning other innovative works on enviromics that can be easily expanded to consider genomic data, like the ones of Fernandes et al. (2024), using machine learning; AraÃºjo et al. (2024), who used GIS data and factor analytic mixed models; and Resende et al. (2024), who propose a new manage for the environmental features before using the reaction norm models.

2 Dataset

The data we will use as an example belongs to the âGenomes to Fieldsâ (G2F) initiative . Here is how G2F is described in their homepage:

âBuilding on prior public funding of plant genome research and operating at a scale necessary to maintain U.S. competitiveness, this Initiative aims to create an interdisciplinary framework for understanding and managing crop performance. Genomes to Fields will not create physical infrastructure but will instead develop a living infrastructure of researchers from many disciplines and a network of field phenotyping sites. The Initiative will generate a large, multi-state, multi-year publicly available dataset of corn phenotype data that will enable researchers to identify connections between variation in heredity material and the environment and the resulting phenotypes (i.e., crop performance). A resource of this type has never before been available to public-sector researchers. A critical part of the Genomes to Fields Initiative is fostering interdisciplinary research collaborations among crop scientists and engineers and computational scientists. The engineers will develop new technologies (e.g., robots and sensors) that will make informative high-throughput phenotyping possible. The computational scientists will develop new computational approaches to analyze the resulting very large (big data) datasets of phenotypes and environmental data and thereby facilitate an understanding of gene function and to address fundamental problems of agricultural productivity. The Initiativeâs interdisciplinary network of scientists and datasets will provide an excellent training platform for students studying agriculture, genetics and engineering.â

Find more information on the initiative here, and other publicy available dataset (phenotypic, genotypic and enviroment) here

3 Single-environment models

Usually, the reaction norm model is fitted using adjusted means (BLUEs). Thus, we have to perform a two-stage analysis, using the genotypic effect as fixed in first step, in single-environment models. These models are be described as follows:

\[ \mathbf{y} = \mathbf{1} \mu + \mathbf{X}_1 \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{X}_2 \mathbf{g} + \boldsymbol{\varepsilon} \]

where \(\mathbf{y}\) is the vector of phenotyes, \(\mu\) is the modelâs intercept, \(\mathbf{b}\) is the vector of fixed block effects, \(\mathbf{g}\) is the vector of fixed genotypic effects, and \(\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\) is the vector of random residual effects \(\left[ \boldsymbol{\varepsilon} \sim \mathcal{N} \left( \mathbf{0}, \sigma^2_\varepsilon \mathbf{I} \right) \right]\). \(\mathbf{1}\) is a vector of ones, and \(\mathbf{X}_1\) and \(\mathbf{X}_2\) are incidence matrices of \(\mathbf{b}\) and \(\mathbf{g}\), respectively.

We will also fit a version of the model above considering the genotypic effect as random \(\left[ \mathbf{g} \sim \mathcal{N} \left( \mathbf{0}, \sigma^2_g \mathbf{I} \right) \right]\), so we can check the effectâs significance via likelihood ratio test (LRT), and estimate the broad-sense heritability. These metrics are calculated as follows:

\[ LRT = -2(logL_r - logL_c) \]

where \(logL_r\) and \(logL_c\) is the logarithm of the residual maximum likelihood function of the reduced and complete models, respectively. The LR statistics is asymptotically distributed as a \(\chi^2 \sim 1\) degree of freedom

\[ H^2 = \frac{\sigma^2_g}{\sigma^2_g + \frac{\sigma^2_\varepsilon}{r}} \]

where \(r\) is the number of blocks.

We also computed the coefficient of experimental variation as:

\[ CV = \frac{\sqrt{\sigma^2_\varepsilon}}{\mu} \]

dat.split = split(x = dat, f = dat$year_loc)

indiv.results = lapply(dat.split, function(x){
  
  message("====> Environment: ", unique(x$year_loc))
  
  x = transform(x, genotype = as.factor(genotype), block = as.factor(block))

  mfix = mmer(fixed = yield ~ block + genotype,
              rcov = ~ units,
              data = x)
  blue = coef(mfix)
  mu = blue[1, 3]
  blue = x |> reframe(yield = mean(yield), .by = c("genotype")) |>
    left_join(
      blue[grepl("genotype", blue$Effect), ] |>
        mutate_at("Effect", str_replace, "genotype", '') |>
        rename(genotype = Effect),
      by = 'genotype'
    ) |>
    mutate(Estimate = ifelse(is.na(Estimate), 0, Estimate) + mu,
           env = unique(x$year_loc)) |> 
    dplyr::select(-Trait, -yield) |> 
    rename(blue = Estimate) |> relocate(env, .before = genotype)
  
  
  mrand = mmer(fixed = yield ~ block, 
                 random = ~ genotype, 
               rcov = ~units,
                 data = x)
  lrtest = anova(mrand, mmer(fixed = yield ~ block, data = x))
  vc = summary(mrand)$varcomp
  
  list(
    params = data.frame(
      s2g = vc[1,1],
      s2e = vc[2,1],
      H2 = vc[1,1]/(vc[1,1] + (vc[2,1]/nlevels(x$block))),
      CV = sqrt(vc[2,1])/mean(x$yield, na.rm = TRUE),
      mu = mean(x$yield, na.rm = TRUE),
      lrt = as.numeric(strsplit(lrtest$PrChisq[2], split = ' ')[[1]][1])
    ),
    blues = blue
  )
})
params = do.call(rbind, lapply(indiv.results, function(x) x$params)) |> 
  rownames_to_column("env")
blues = do.call(rbind, lapply(indiv.results, function(x) x$blues)) |> 
  filter(env %in% params[which(!params$lrt > 0.05), 'env'])

3.1 Graphical overview

Some plots can help us understand the dataset. For instance, FigureÂ 2 shows that some environments seem to be more suitable for grain yield, a first evidence of genotype-by-environment interaction (GEI). FigureÂ 3 is the final evidence we needed: genotypes have a different performance according to the environment they are tested. This is the core idea of GEI.

params |> ggplot(aes(x = reorder(env, -mu), y = mu)) + 
  geom_col(colour = 'black', aes(fill = mu)) + theme_bw() + 
  theme(legend.position = 'none', 
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust = 1)) + 
  labs(x = "Environments", y = "Grain yield (tons per hectare)") +

  geom_tile() + theme_bw() + 
  theme(legend.position = 'top', 
        axis.text.x = element_blank(), legend.title.position = 'top') +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = 'inferno') + 
  labs(x = "Genotypes", y = "Environments", fill = "GY (tons per hectare)")

FigureÂ 4 depicts the experimental precison of each environment (a visualization also used in Chaves et al., 2024). The ideal is that trials have a low CV and a high \(H^2\) (which will depend on the assessed trait, population, etc.). For instance, 2017-TXH1-Early is the most precise trial. 2017-ILH1 had a nil broad-sense heritability. Indeed, when we check FigureÂ 5, this environment had \(\sigma^2_g = 0\). This explains why the P-value of the LRT indicates the non-rejection of the null hyphotesis.

4 Molecular data

Now that the first stage is completed, letâs manage the molecular data. The matrix of molecular markers contains 98,026 SNP available for almost all assessed genotypes. Before using it the build the genomic relationship matrix (GRM), we made some quality control in the SNP matrix by keeping markers with maximum minor allele frequency of 5%. After filtering, 89,836 markers remained. With them, we built the GRM as:

\[ \mathbf{G} = \frac{\mathbf{M}^\prime \mathbf{M}}{p} \]

where \(\mathbf{M}\) is the scaled and centered SNP matrix, and \(p\) is the number of columns of \(\mathbf{M}\), i.e., the number of SNPs.

geno = as.data.frame(data.table::fread(file = 'data/GENO.csv'))
rownames(geno) = NULL; rownames(geno) = geno[,1]; geno = geno[,-1]; geno = as.matrix(geno)
geno = geno[which(rownames(geno) %in% unique(blues$genotype)),]
dim(geno)
matnames = dimnames(geno)
geno[1:5,1:5]

# MAF
freq <- apply(geno, 2, function(x) {
  mean(x, na.rm = TRUE)
})/2
MAF <- apply(rbind(freq, 1 - freq), 2, min)

geno = geno[,-which(MAF < 0.05)]
dim(geno)
G = tcrossprod(apply(geno, 2, scale))/ncol(geno)
rownames(G) = colnames(G) = rownames(geno$M.clean)

The code above takes time, so letâs just load the GRM:

Gmat = readRDS(file = "Gmat.rds")

5 Environmental data

Now letâs handle the environmental data:

envcov = read.csv(file = 'data/ECOV.csv')
colnames(envcov)[1] = "env"

There are 202 environmental features. These features are divided according to maizeâs physiological phases: germination, emergence, juvenile phase, floral initiation, flag leaf emergence, flowering, grain filling, maturity and harvesting. For more details, check the file âECOV_periodâ.

The first step is to remove the environments discarded due to non-significance of genotypic effects from the envcov object:

envcov = envcov[which(envcov$env %in% blues$env),]

Now, we build \(\mathbf{W}\), the scaled and centred matrix of enviromental features. With it, we build \(\mathbf{\Omega}\), the environmental kernel (or a kind of âenvironmental relationship matrixâ):

\[ \mathbf{\Omega} = \frac{\mathbf{W}^\prime \mathbf{W}}{q} \]

with \(q\) being the number of columns of \(\mathbf{W}\).

rownames(envcov) = envcov[,1]; envcov = envcov[,-1]
W = scale(envcov, center = TRUE, scale = TRUE)
Omega = tcrossprod(W)/ncol(W)
dim(Omega)
[1] 31 31

6 Second-stage analysis

The second-stage analysis are done using the BLUEs from the fist stage. But before delving into the analyses, there are some preparations we have to do first.

6.1 Design matrices

In the second stage, we will use the BGLR package. To use it, we have to build the covariance matrices and construct the linear predictor. But first, letâs build the design matrices for our two effects: environment (say, \(\mathbf{Z}_1\)) and hybrids (letâs call it \(\mathbf{Z}_2\)).

Zenv = model.matrix(~-1 + env, data = blues)
colnames(Zenv) = gsub("env", "", colnames(Zenv))
Zhyb = model.matrix(~-1 + genotype, data = blues)
colnames(Zhyb) = gsub("genotype", "", colnames(Zhyb))

rownames(Zenv) = rownames(Zhyb) = blues$genotype

6.2 Covariance matrices

According to Jarquin et al. (2014), an effective way of considering the interaction between molecular markers and environmental features is by using a multiplicative model, essentially like:

\[ y_i = \mu + w_i + g_i + gw_i + \varepsilon_i \]

The covariance structure of \(gw_i\) is \(\mathbf{gw} \sim \mathcal{N}(\mathbf{0}, \mathbf{G} \# \mathbf{\Omega})\), with \(\#\) representing the Hadamard (point-by-point) product. In most cases, \(\mathbf{G}\) and \(\mathbf{\Omega}\) are non-compatible, This is why we build the design matrices first. By doing matrix operations between the genomic and environmental kernels and the design matrices, we make all matrices readily compatible. Another important detail that you will note in the code below is that we build the covariance functions of both the genotype-by-environmental features (G\(\omega\)I) interaction and the genotype-by-environment interaction. Both interactions will be used in our model. The idea is that the missing environmental factors that could not be accounted by G\(\omega\)I are captured by the GEI component.

ZGZ_hyb = tcrossprod(tcrossprod(Zhyb, Gmat), Zhyb)
ZOZ_env = tcrossprod(tcrossprod(Zenv, Omega), Zenv)
ZZ_env = tcrossprod(Zenv)
GEIO_H = ZGZ_hyb * ZOZ_env
GEI_H = ZGZ_hyb * ZZ_env

This leads to the following model:

\[ \mathbf{\overline{y}} = \mathbf{1}\mu + \mathbf{Z}_1 \mathbf{e} + \mathbf{Z}_2 \mathbf{g} + \mathbf{Z}_3 \mathbf{ge} + \mathbf{Z}_4 \mathbf{g \boldsymbol{\omega}} + \boldsymbol{\varepsilon} \]

with \(\mathbf{e} \stackrel{i.i.d.}{\sim} NMV(\mathbf{0}, \sigma^2_e \mathbf{I})\), \(\mathbf{g} \stackrel{i.i.d.}{\sim} NMV(\mathbf{0}, \sigma^2_g \mathbf{G})\), \(\mathbf{ge} \stackrel{i.i.d.}{\sim} NMV[\mathbf{0}, \sigma^2_{ge} (\mathbf{Z}_2 \mathbf{G}_A \mathbf{Z}_2' \# \mathbf{Z}_1 \mathbf{Z}_1')]\), and \(\mathbf{g\boldsymbol{\omega}} \stackrel{i.i.d.}{\sim} NMV[\mathbf{0}, \sigma^2_{g\omega} (\mathbf{Z}_2 \mathbf{G} \mathbf{Z}_2' \# \mathbf{Z}_1 \mathbf{\Omega} \mathbf{Z}_1')]\).

6.3 Genomic prediction

To fit models in BGLR, we must first build the ETA object. Here, we define the model for each effect. This model refers to how the package will deal with a given effect. The RKHS (acronym for Reproducing Kernel Hilbert Space) is an equivalent to the GBLUP.

ETA = list(
  env = list(V = eigen(ZZ_env)$vectors, d = eigen(ZZ_env)$values, model = 'RKHS'),
  hyb = list(V = eigen(ZGZ_hyb)$vectors, d = eigen(ZGZ_hyb)$values, model = 'RKHS'),
  gei = list(V = eigen(GEI_H)$vectors, d = eigen(GEI_H)$values, model = 'RKHS'),
  gwi = list(V = eigen(GEIO_H)$vectors, d = eigen(GEIO_H)$values, model = 'RKHS')
)

6.3.1 Leave-one-out cross-validation

Letâs check how well the model predicts untested environments. This is done using a leave-one-environment-out cross-validation procedure. To show how this validation is data-dependent, we will use two environments as examples:

  • Environment â2016-DEH1â
yNA = blues$blue
yNA[which(blues$env == '2016-DEH1')] = NA

cvmod = BGLR::BGLR(y = yNA, ETA = ETA, nIter = 12000, burnIn = 2000)
unlink("*.dat")

predvals = cbind(
  blues[which(blues$env == '2016-DEH1'),c('hybrid','env','blue')],
  yhat = cvmod$yHat[which(blues$env == '2016-DEH1')]
)
load(file = "predvals_DEH1.RDA")
cor(predvals$blue, predvals$yhat)
[1] 0.742526
mean(predvals$yhat - predvals$blue)^2
[1] 2.190748
  • Environment â2017-NYH3â
yNA = blues$blue
yNA[which(blues$env == '2017-NYH3')] = NA

cvmod = BGLR::BGLR(y = yNA, ETA = ETA, nIter = 12000, burnIn = 2000)
unlink("*.dat")

predvals = cbind(
  blues[which(blues$env == '2017-NYH3'),c('hybrid','env','blue')],
  yhat = cvmod$yHat[which(blues$env == '2017-NYH3')]
)
load(file = "predvals_NYH3.RDA")
cor(predvals$blue, predvals$yhat)
[1] 0.4114012
mean(predvals$yhat - predvals$blue)^2
[1] 0.9656543

Environment â2016-DEH1â is better predicted than environment â2017-NYH3â. This is probably due to a more representativeness of the former in terms of tested genotypes and sampled environmental conditions.

# Introduction {.justify}

In this tutorial, we show a detailed guide on how to fit reaction norm models accounting for both genomics and enviromics information. This method was first proposed by @jarquin_reaction_2014, and was latter expanded and used by several research groups [@costa-neto_nonlinear_2021;@de_los_campos_data-driven_2020;@toda_reaction_2024]. This was one of the first initiatives for integrating genomics and enviromics in plant breeding. It is worth mentioning other innovative works on enviromics that can be easily expanded to consider genomic data, like the ones of @fernandes_using_2024, using machine learning; @araujo_gis-fa_2024, who used GIS data and factor analytic mixed models; and @resende_gis-based_2024, who propose a new manage for the environmental features before using the reaction norm models.

# Dataset {.justify}

The data we will use as an example belongs to the "Genomes to Fields" (G2F) initiative . Here is how G2F is described in their homepage:

"Building on prior public funding of plant genome research and operating at a scale necessary to maintain U.S. competitiveness, this Initiative aims to create an interdisciplinary framework for understanding and managing crop performance. Genomes to Fields will not create physical infrastructure but will instead develop a living infrastructure of researchers from many disciplines and a network of field phenotyping sites. The Initiative will generate a large, multi-state, multi-year publicly available dataset of corn phenotype data that will enable researchers to identify connections between variation in heredity material and the environment and the resulting phenotypes (i.e., crop performance). A resource of this type has never before been available to public-sector researchers. A critical part of the Genomes to Fields Initiative is fostering interdisciplinary research collaborations among crop scientists and engineers and computational scientists. The engineers will develop new technologies (e.g., robots and sensors) that will make informative high-throughput phenotyping possible. The computational scientists will develop new computational approaches to analyze the resulting very large (big data) datasets of phenotypes and environmental data and thereby facilitate an understanding of gene function and to address fundamental problems of agricultural productivity. The Initiativeâs interdisciplinary network of scientists and datasets will provide an excellent training platform for students studying agriculture, genetics and engineering."

Find more information on the initiative [here](https://www.genomes2fields.org/home/), and other publicy available dataset (phenotypic, genotypic and enviroment) [here](https://www.genomes2fields.org/resources/)

# Single-environment models {.justify}

Usually, the reaction norm model is fitted using adjusted means (BLUEs). Thus, we have to perform a two-stage analysis, using the genotypic effect as fixed in first step, in single-environment models. These models are be described as follows:

$$
\mathbf{y} = \mathbf{1} \mu +  \mathbf{X}_1 \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{X}_2 \mathbf{g} + \boldsymbol{\varepsilon}
$$

where $\mathbf{y}$ is the vector of phenotyes, $\mu$ is the model's intercept, $\mathbf{b}$ is the vector of fixed block effects, $\mathbf{g}$ is the vector of fixed genotypic effects, and $\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$ is the vector of random residual effects $\left[ \boldsymbol{\varepsilon} \sim \mathcal{N} \left( \mathbf{0}, \sigma^2_\varepsilon \mathbf{I} \right)  \right]$. $\mathbf{1}$ is a vector of ones, and $\mathbf{X}_1$ and $\mathbf{X}_2$ are incidence matrices of $\mathbf{b}$ and $\mathbf{g}$, respectively. 

We will also fit a version of the model above considering the genotypic effect as random $\left[ \mathbf{g} \sim \mathcal{N} \left( \mathbf{0}, \sigma^2_g \mathbf{I} \right)  \right]$, so we can check the effect's significance via likelihood ratio test (LRT), and estimate the broad-sense heritability. These metrics are calculated as follows:

$$
LRT = -2(logL_r - logL_c)
$$

where $logL_r$ and $logL_c$ is the logarithm of the residual maximum likelihood function of the reduced and complete models, respectively. The LR statistics is asymptotically distributed as a $\chi^2 \sim 1$ degree of freedom

$$
H^2 = \frac{\sigma^2_g}{\sigma^2_g + \frac{\sigma^2_\varepsilon}{r}}
$$

where $r$ is the number of blocks. 

We also computed the coefficient of experimental variation as:

$$
CV = \frac{\sqrt{\sigma^2_\varepsilon}}{\mu}
$$

```{r echo=TRUE, warning=FALSE, results='hide', message=FALSE}
dat.split = split(x = dat, f = dat$year_loc)

indiv.results = lapply(dat.split, function(x){
  
  message("====> Environment: ", unique(x$year_loc))
  
  x = transform(x, genotype = as.factor(genotype), block = as.factor(block))

  mfix = mmer(fixed = yield ~ block + genotype,
              rcov = ~ units,
              data = x)
  blue = coef(mfix)
  mu = blue[1, 3]
  blue = x |> reframe(yield = mean(yield), .by = c("genotype")) |>
    left_join(
      blue[grepl("genotype", blue$Effect), ] |>
        mutate_at("Effect", str_replace, "genotype", '') |>
        rename(genotype = Effect),
      by = 'genotype'
    ) |>
    mutate(Estimate = ifelse(is.na(Estimate), 0, Estimate) + mu,
           env = unique(x$year_loc)) |> 
    dplyr::select(-Trait, -yield) |> 
    rename(blue = Estimate) |> relocate(env, .before = genotype)
  
  
  mrand = mmer(fixed = yield ~ block, 
                 random = ~ genotype, 
               rcov = ~units,
                 data = x)
  lrtest = anova(mrand, mmer(fixed = yield ~ block, data = x))
  vc = summary(mrand)$varcomp
  
  list(
    params = data.frame(
      s2g = vc[1,1],
      s2e = vc[2,1],
      H2 = vc[1,1]/(vc[1,1] + (vc[2,1]/nlevels(x$block))),
      CV = sqrt(vc[2,1])/mean(x$yield, na.rm = TRUE),
      mu = mean(x$yield, na.rm = TRUE),
      lrt = as.numeric(strsplit(lrtest$PrChisq[2], split = ' ')[[1]][1])
    ),
    blues = blue
  )
})
params = do.call(rbind, lapply(indiv.results, function(x) x$params)) |> 
  rownames_to_column("env")
blues = do.call(rbind, lapply(indiv.results, function(x) x$blues)) |> 
  filter(env %in% params[which(!params$lrt > 0.05), 'env'])
```

# Molecular data {.justify}

Now that the first stage is completed, let's manage the molecular data. The matrix of molecular markers contains 98,026 SNP available for almost all assessed genotypes. Before using it the build the genomic relationship matrix (GRM), we made some quality control in the SNP matrix by keeping markers with maximum minor allele frequency of 5\%. After filtering, 89,836 markers remained. With them, we built the GRM as:

$$
\mathbf{G} = \frac{\mathbf{M}^\prime \mathbf{M}}{p}
$$

where $\mathbf{M}$ is the scaled and centered SNP matrix, and $p$ is the number of columns of $\mathbf{M}$, i.e., the number of SNPs. 

```{r echo=TRUE, eval=FALSE}
geno = as.data.frame(data.table::fread(file = 'data/GENO.csv'))
rownames(geno) = NULL; rownames(geno) = geno[,1]; geno = geno[,-1]; geno = as.matrix(geno)
geno = geno[which(rownames(geno) %in% unique(blues$genotype)),]
dim(geno)
matnames = dimnames(geno)
geno[1:5,1:5]

# MAF
freq <- apply(geno, 2, function(x) {
  mean(x, na.rm = TRUE)
})/2
MAF <- apply(rbind(freq, 1 - freq), 2, min)

geno = geno[,-which(MAF < 0.05)]
dim(geno)
G = tcrossprod(apply(geno, 2, scale))/ncol(geno)
rownames(G) = colnames(G) = rownames(geno$M.clean)
```

The code above takes time, so let's just load the GRM:

```{r echo=TRUE}
Gmat = readRDS(file = "Gmat.rds")
dim(Gmat)
```

# Environmental data {.justify}

Now let's handle the environmental data: 

```{r echo=TRUE}
envcov = read.csv(file = 'data/ECOV.csv')
colnames(envcov)[1] = "env"
```

There are `r ncol(envcov)-1` environmental features. These features are divided according to maize's physiological phases: germination, emergence, juvenile phase, floral initiation, flag leaf emergence, flowering, grain filling, maturity and harvesting. For more details, check the file "ECOV_period".

The first step is to remove the environments discarded due to non-significance of genotypic effects from the `envcov` object: 

```{r echo=TRUE}
envcov = envcov[which(envcov$env %in% blues$env),]
```

Now, we build $\mathbf{W}$, the scaled and centred matrix of enviromental features. With it, we build $\mathbf{\Omega}$, the environmental kernel (or a kind of "environmental relationship matrix"):

$$
\mathbf{\Omega} = \frac{\mathbf{W}^\prime \mathbf{W}}{q}
$$

with $q$ being the number of columns of $\mathbf{W}$.

```{r echo=TRUE}
rownames(envcov) = envcov[,1]; envcov = envcov[,-1]
W = scale(envcov, center = TRUE, scale = TRUE)
Omega = tcrossprod(W)/ncol(W)
dim(Omega)
```


# Second-stage analysis {.justify}

The second-stage analysis are done using the BLUEs from the fist stage. But before delving into the analyses, there are some preparations we have to do first.

## Design matrices

In the second stage, we will use the `BGLR` package. To use it, we have to build the covariance matrices and construct the linear predictor. But first, let's build the design matrices for our two effects: environment (say, $\mathbf{Z}_1$) and hybrids (let's call it $\mathbf{Z}_2$).

```{r echo=TRUE}
Zenv = model.matrix(~-1 + env, data = blues)
colnames(Zenv) = gsub("env", "", colnames(Zenv))
Zhyb = model.matrix(~-1 + genotype, data = blues)
colnames(Zhyb) = gsub("genotype", "", colnames(Zhyb))

rownames(Zenv) = rownames(Zhyb) = blues$genotype
```

## Covariance matrices

According to @jarquin_reaction_2014, an effective way of considering the interaction between molecular markers and environmental features is by using a multiplicative model, essentially like: 

$$
y_i = \mu + w_i + g_i + gw_i + \varepsilon_i
$$

The covariance structure of $gw_i$ is $\mathbf{gw} \sim \mathcal{N}(\mathbf{0}, \mathbf{G} \# \mathbf{\Omega})$, with $\#$ representing the Hadamard (point-by-point) product. In most cases, $\mathbf{G}$ and $\mathbf{\Omega}$ are non-compatible, This is why we build the design matrices first. By doing matrix operations between the genomic and environmental kernels and the design matrices, we make all matrices readily compatible. Another important detail that you will note in the code below is that we build the covariance functions of both the genotype-by-environmental features (G$\omega$I) interaction and the genotype-by-environment interaction. Both interactions will be used in our model. The idea is that the missing environmental factors that could not be accounted by G$\omega$I are captured by the GEI component.

```{r echo=TRUE}
ZGZ_hyb = tcrossprod(tcrossprod(Zhyb, Gmat), Zhyb)
ZOZ_env = tcrossprod(tcrossprod(Zenv, Omega), Zenv)
ZZ_env = tcrossprod(Zenv)
GEIO_H = ZGZ_hyb * ZOZ_env
GEI_H = ZGZ_hyb * ZZ_env
```

This leads to the following model:

$$
\mathbf{\overline{y}} = \mathbf{1}\mu + \mathbf{Z}_1 \mathbf{e} + \mathbf{Z}_2 \mathbf{g} + \mathbf{Z}_3 \mathbf{ge} + \mathbf{Z}_4 \mathbf{g \boldsymbol{\omega}}  + \boldsymbol{\varepsilon}
$$

with $\mathbf{e} \stackrel{i.i.d.}{\sim} NMV(\mathbf{0}, \sigma^2_e \mathbf{I})$, $\mathbf{g} \stackrel{i.i.d.}{\sim} NMV(\mathbf{0}, \sigma^2_g \mathbf{G})$, $\mathbf{ge} \stackrel{i.i.d.}{\sim} NMV[\mathbf{0}, \sigma^2_{ge} (\mathbf{Z}_2 \mathbf{G}_A \mathbf{Z}_2' \# \mathbf{Z}_1 \mathbf{Z}_1')]$, and $\mathbf{g\boldsymbol{\omega}} \stackrel{i.i.d.}{\sim} NMV[\mathbf{0}, \sigma^2_{g\omega} (\mathbf{Z}_2 \mathbf{G} \mathbf{Z}_2' \# \mathbf{Z}_1 \mathbf{\Omega} \mathbf{Z}_1')]$.

## Genomic prediction

To fit models in `BGLR`, we must first build the `ETA` object. Here, we define the model for each effect. This model refers to how the package will deal with a given effect. The RKHS (acronym for Reproducing Kernel Hilbert Space) is an equivalent to the GBLUP.

```{r echo=TRUE, eval=FALSE}
ETA = list(
  env = list(V = eigen(ZZ_env)$vectors, d = eigen(ZZ_env)$values, model = 'RKHS'),
  hyb = list(V = eigen(ZGZ_hyb)$vectors, d = eigen(ZGZ_hyb)$values, model = 'RKHS'),
  gei = list(V = eigen(GEI_H)$vectors, d = eigen(GEI_H)$values, model = 'RKHS'),
  gwi = list(V = eigen(GEIO_H)$vectors, d = eigen(GEIO_H)$values, model = 'RKHS')
)
```

### Leave-one-out cross-validation

Let's check how well the model predicts untested environments. This is done using a leave-one-environment-out cross-validation procedure. To show how this validation is data-dependent, we will use two environments as examples:

-   Environment "2016-DEH1"

```{r echo=TRUE, eval=FALSE}
yNA = blues$blue
yNA[which(blues$env == '2016-DEH1')] = NA

cvmod = BGLR::BGLR(y = yNA, ETA = ETA, nIter = 12000, burnIn = 2000)
unlink("*.dat")

predvals = cbind(
  blues[which(blues$env == '2016-DEH1'),c('hybrid','env','blue')],
  yhat = cvmod$yHat[which(blues$env == '2016-DEH1')]
)
```


```{r echo=TRUE}
load(file = "predvals_DEH1.RDA")
cor(predvals$blue, predvals$yhat)
mean(predvals$yhat - predvals$blue)^2
```

-   Environment "2017-NYH3"

```{r echo=TRUE, eval=FALSE}
yNA = blues$blue
yNA[which(blues$env == '2017-NYH3')] = NA

cvmod = BGLR::BGLR(y = yNA, ETA = ETA, nIter = 12000, burnIn = 2000)
unlink("*.dat")

predvals = cbind(
  blues[which(blues$env == '2017-NYH3'),c('hybrid','env','blue')],
  yhat = cvmod$yHat[which(blues$env == '2017-NYH3')]
)
```

```{r echo=TRUE}
load(file = "predvals_NYH3.RDA")
cor(predvals$blue, predvals$yhat)
mean(predvals$yhat - predvals$blue)^2
```

Environment "2016-DEH1" is better predicted than environment "2017-NYH3". This is probably due to a more representativeness of the former in terms of tested genotypes and sampled environmental conditions.
